{"key":"post-11475545","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11475545</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Ive had coffee grinds sitting in a bucket with the lid closed for awhile (weeks).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not good.&amp;nbsp; Always dry them completely and store in an open container to prevent molds and bacteria.&amp;nbsp; If they're wet at all or smell like anything but coffee, I'd toss them and get fresh ones.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I wanted to add them to coir and have them be pasteurized with the coir (by adding boiling water to the coir in a bucket then putting a lid on the bucket).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That isn't pasteurization, it's partial sterilization and a poor method at that.&amp;nbsp; The material gets above pasteurization temps at first, but before the hour is up, drops well below pasteurization temperature.&amp;nbsp; It works with coir because you could use no pasteurization at all with coir and succeed.&amp;nbsp; Used with coffee, straw, compost, manure, etc., it's going to have a high failure rate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To pasteurize, heat your material to 140F/60C and keep it there for an hour to 90 minutes.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11475549</next>\n<prev>11475521</prev>\n<first>11475444</first>\n<last>11475913</last>\n<when>1258505838</when>\n<utime>11/18/09 02:57 AM</utime>\n</post>"}